This paper deals with the algorithmic complexity of solving stochastic games, which is a topic in game theory (cs.GT). The paper also involves the analysis of graphs and their properties, which falls under the category of data structures and algorithms (cs.DS). Additionally, the paper proposes an algorithm for solving these games, which involves decision-making and optimization, making it relevant to artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and machine learning (cs.LG). Finally, the paper involves the analysis of probabilities and transitions, which is a topic in computational complexity theory (cs.CC).
